The paper deals with the problem of finding conditions under which the iterated hairpin completion of a given word is regular, which is a combinatorial and algebraic problem. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-categories. The paper also involves the classification of the set of all words based on the numbers of words $\alpha$ and $\calpha$ that initiate hairpin completion and how they are scattered, which is related to the Graph Theory (cs.GT) and Combinatorics (cs.CC) sub-categories. Finally, the paper may involve some computational aspects, such as the complexity of the algorithms used to determine the regularity of the iterated hairpin completion, which is related to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
